# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bristol-409
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] The usual waveform of alternating current in most electric power circuits is a sine wave, whose positive half-period corresponds with positive direction of the current and vice versa (the full period is called a *cycle*).
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] "Alternating current" most commonly refers to power distribution, but a wide range of other applications are technically alternating current although it is less common to describe them by that term.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] In many applications, like guitar amplifiers, different waveforms are used, such as triangular waves or square waves.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] Audio and radio signals carried on electrical wires are also examples of alternating current.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] These types of alternating current carry information such as sound (audio) or images (video) sometimes carried by modulation of an AC carrier signal.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] These currents typically alternate at higher frequencies than those used in power transmission.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] Electrical energy is distributed as alternating current because AC voltage may be increased or decreased with a transformer.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] This allows the power to be transmitted through power lines efficiently at high voltage, which reduces the energy lost as heat due to resistance of the wire, and transformed to a lower, safer voltage for use.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] Use of a higher voltage leads to significantly more efficient transmission of power.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] This means that when transmitting a fixed power on a given wire, if the current is halved (by doubling the voltage), the power loss due to the wire's resistance will be reduced by a factor of four.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] Consequently, power transmitted at a higher voltage requires less loss-producing current than for the same power at a lower voltage.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] Power is often transmitted at hundreds of kilovolts on pylons, and transformed down to tens of kilovolts to be transmitted on lower level lines, and finally transformed down to 100 V – 240 V for domestic use.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] High voltages have disadvantages, such as the increased insulation required, and generally increased difficulty in their safe handling.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] In a power plant, energy is generated at a convenient voltage for the design of a generator, and then stepped up to a high voltage for transmission.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] Near the loads, the transmission voltage is stepped down to the voltages used by equipment.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] Consumer voltages vary somewhat depending on the country and size of load, but generally motors and lighting are built to use up to a few hundred volts between phases.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] The voltage delivered to equipment such as lighting and motor loads is standardized, with an allowable range of voltage over which equipment is expected to operate.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] Standard power utilization voltages and percentage tolerance vary in the different mains power systems found in the world.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] High-voltage direct-current (HVDC) electric power transmission systems have become more viable as technology has provided efficient means of changing the voltage of DC power.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] Transmission with high voltage direct current was not feasible in the early days of electric power transmission, as there was then no economically viable way to step the voltage of DC down for end user applications such as lighting incandescent bulbs.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] Three-phase electrical generation is very common.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] The simplest way is to use three separate coils in the generator stator, physically offset by an angle of 120° (one-third of a complete 360° phase) to each other.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] Three current waveforms are produced that are equal in magnitude and 120° out of phase to each other.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] If coils are added opposite to these (60° spacing), they generate the same phases with reverse polarity and can be wired together.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] In practice, higher *pole orders* are commonly used.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] For example, a 12-pole machine would have 36 coils (10° spacing).
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] The advantage is that lower rotational speeds can be used to generate the same frequency.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] For example, a 2-pole machine running at 3600 rpm and a 12-pole machine running at 600 rpm produce the same frequency; the lower speed is preferable for larger machines.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] If the load on a three-phase system is balanced equally among the phases, no current flows through the neutral point.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] Even in the worst-case unbalanced (linear) load, the neutral current will not exceed the highest of the phase currents.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] Non-linear loads (e.g. the switch-mode power supplies widely used) may require an oversized neutral bus and neutral conductor in the upstream distribution panel to handle harmonics.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] Harmonics can cause neutral conductor current levels to exceed that of one or all phase conductors.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] For three-phase at utilization voltages a four-wire system is often used.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] When stepping down three-phase, a transformer with a Delta (3-wire) primary and a Star (4-wire, center-earthed) secondary is often used so there is no need for a neutral on the supply side.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] For smaller customers (just how small varies by country and age of the installation) only a single phase and neutral, or two phases and neutral, are taken to the property.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] For larger installations, all three phases and neutral are taken to the main distribution panel.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] From the three-phase main panel, both single and three-phase circuits may lead off.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] Three-wire single-phase systems, with a single center-tapped transformer giving two live conductors, is a common distribution scheme for residential and small commercial buildings in North America.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] This arrangement is sometimes incorrectly referred to as *two phase*.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] A similar method is used for a different reason on construction sites in the UK.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] Small power tools and lighting are supposed to be supplied by a local center-tapped transformer with a voltage of 55 V between each power conductor and earth.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] This significantly reduces the risk of electric shock in the event that one of the live conductors becomes exposed through an equipment fault whilst still allowing a reasonable voltage of 110 V between the two conductors for running the tools.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] An additional wire, called the bond (or earth) wire, is often connected between non-current-carrying metal enclosures and earth ground.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] This conductor provides protection from electric shock due to accidental contact of circuit conductors with the metal chassis of portable appliances and tools.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] Bonding all non-current-carrying metal parts into one complete system ensures there is always a low electrical impedance path to ground sufficient to carry any fault current for as long as it takes for the system to clear the fault.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] This low impedance path allows the maximum amount of fault current, causing the overcurrent protection device (breakers, fuses) to trip or burn out as quickly as possible, bringing the electrical system to a safe state.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] All bond wires are bonded to ground at the main service panel, as is the neutral/identified conductor if present.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] The frequency of the electrical system varies by country and sometimes within a country; most electric power is generated at either 50 or 60 Hz.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] Some countries have a mixture of 50 Hz and 60 Hz supplies, notably electricity power transmission in Japan.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] A low frequency eases the design of electric motors, particularly for hoisting, crushing and rolling applications, and commutator-type traction motors for applications such as railways.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] However, low frequency also causes noticeable flicker in arc lamps and incandescent light bulbs.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] The use of lower frequencies also provided the advantage of lower transmission losses, which are proportional to frequency.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] The original Niagara Falls generators were built to produce 25 Hz power, as a compromise between low frequency for traction and heavy induction motors, while still allowing incandescent lighting to operate (although with noticeable flicker).
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] Most of the 25 Hz residential and commercial customers for Niagara Falls power were converted to 60 Hz by the late 1950s, although some 25 Hz industrial customers still existed as of the start of the 21st century.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] 16.7 Hz power (formerly 16 2/3 Hz) is still used in some European rail systems, such as in Austria, Germany, Norway, Sweden and Switzerland.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] Off-shore, military, textile industry, marine, aircraft, and spacecraft applications sometimes use 400 Hz, for benefits of reduced weight of apparatus or higher motor speeds.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] Computer mainframe systems were often powered by 400 Hz or 415 Hz for benefits of ripple reduction while using smaller internal AC to DC conversion units.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] A direct current flows uniformly throughout the cross-section of a homogeneous electrically conducting wire.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] An alternating current of any frequency is forced away from the wire's center, toward its outer surface.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] This is because an alternating current (which is the result of the acceleration of electric charge) creates electromagnetic waves (a phenomenon known as electromagnetic radiation).
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] The phenomenon of alternating current being pushed away from the center of the conductor is called skin effect, and a direct current does not exhibit this effect, since a direct current does not create electromagnetic waves.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] At very high frequencies, the current no longer flows *in* the wire, but effectively flows *on* the surface of the wire, within a thickness of a few skin depths.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] The skin depth is the thickness at which the current density is reduced by 63%.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] Even at relatively low frequencies used for power transmission (50 Hz – 60 Hz), non-uniform distribution of current still occurs in sufficiently thick conductors.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] For example, the skin depth of a copper conductor is approximately 8.57 mm at 60 Hz, so high-current conductors are usually hollow to reduce their mass and cost.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] This tendency of alternating current to flow predominantly in the periphery of conductors reduces the effective cross-section of the conductor.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] This increases the effective AC resistance of the conductor since resistance is inversely proportional to the cross-sectional area.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] A conductor's AC resistance is higher than its DC resistance, causing a higher energy loss due to Ohmic heating (also called I2R loss).
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] For low to medium frequencies, conductors can be divided into stranded wires, each insulated from the others, with the relative positions of individual strands specially arranged within the conductor bundle.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] Wire constructed using this technique is called Litz wire.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] This measure helps to partially mitigate skin effect by forcing more equal current throughout the total cross section of the stranded conductors.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] As written above, an alternating current is made of electric charge under periodic acceleration, which causes radiation of electromagnetic waves.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] Depending on the frequency, different techniques are used to minimize the loss due to radiation.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] At frequencies up to about 1 GHz, pairs of wires are twisted together in a cable, forming a twisted pair.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] This reduces losses from electromagnetic radiation and inductive coupling.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] A twisted pair must be used with a balanced signaling system so that the two wires carry equal but opposite currents.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] Each wire in a twisted pair radiates a signal, but it is effectively canceled by radiation from the other wire, resulting in almost no radiation loss.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] Coaxial cables are commonly used at audio frequencies and above for convenience.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] A coaxial cable has a conductive wire inside a conductive tube, separated by a dielectric layer.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] The current flowing on the surface of the inner conductor is equal and opposite to the current flowing on the inner surface of the outer tube.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] The electromagnetic field is thus completely contained within the tube, and (ideally) no energy is lost to radiation or coupling outside the tube.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] Coaxial cables have acceptably small losses for frequencies up to about 5 GHz.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] For microwave frequencies greater than 5 GHz, the losses (due mainly to the dielectric separating the inner and outer tubes being a non-ideal insulator) become too large, making waveguides a more efficient medium for transmitting energy.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] Coaxial cables often use a perforated dielectric layer to separate the inner and outer conductors in order to minimize the power dissipated by the dielectric.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] Waveguides are similar to coaxial cables, as both consist of tubes, with the biggest difference being that waveguides have no inner conductor.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] Waveguides can have any arbitrary cross section, but rectangular cross sections are the most common.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] Because waveguides do not have an inner conductor to carry a return current, waveguides cannot deliver energy by means of an electric current, but rather by means of a *guided* electromagnetic field.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] Although surface currents do flow on the inner walls of the waveguides, those surface currents do not carry power.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] Power is carried by the guided electromagnetic fields.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] The surface currents are set up by the guided electromagnetic fields and have the effect of keeping the fields inside the waveguide and preventing leakage of the fields to the space outside the waveguide.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] Waveguides have dimensions comparable to the wavelength of the alternating current to be transmitted, so they are feasible only at microwave frequencies.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] In addition to this mechanical feasibility, electrical resistance of the non-ideal metals forming the walls of the waveguide causes dissipation of power (surface currents flowing on lossy conductors dissipate power).
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] At higher frequencies, the power lost to this dissipation becomes unacceptably large.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] At frequencies greater than 200 GHz, waveguide dimensions become impractically small, and the ohmic losses in the waveguide walls become large.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] Instead, fiber optics, which are a form of dielectric waveguides, can be used.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] For such frequencies, the concepts of voltages and currents are no longer used.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] Alternating currents are accompanied (or caused) by alternating voltages.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] The peak-to-peak value of an AC voltage is defined as the difference between its positive peak and its negative peak.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] Since the maximum value of $\sin(x)$ is +1 and the minimum value is −1, an AC voltage swings between $+V_{\text{peak}}$ and $-V_{\text{peak}}$ .
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] Below an AC waveform (with no DC component) is assumed.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] The RMS voltage is the square root of the mean over one cycle of the square of the instantaneous voltage.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] Rather than using instantaneous power, $p(t)$ , it is more practical to use a time-averaged power (where the averaging is performed over any integer number of cycles).
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] For this reason, AC power's waveform becomes Full-wave rectified sine, and its fundamental frequency is double that of the voltage's.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] To illustrate these concepts, consider a 230 V AC mains supply used in many countries around the world.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] It is so called because its root mean square value is 230 V.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] This means that the time-averaged power delivered $P_{\text{average}}$ is equivalent to the power delivered by a DC voltage of 230 V.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] For 230 V AC, the peak voltage $V_{\text{peak}}$ is therefore $230{\text{ V}}\times {\sqrt {2}}$ , which is about 325 V, and the peak power $P_{\text{peak}}$ is $230\times R\times W\times 2$ , that is 460 RW.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] During the course of one cycle (two cycle as the power) the voltage rises from zero to 325 V, the power from zero to 460 RW, and both falls through zero.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] Next, the voltage descends to reverse direction, −325 V, but the power ascends again to 460 RW, and both returns to zero.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] Alternating current is used to transmit information, as in the cases of telephone and cable television.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] Information signals are carried over a wide range of AC frequencies.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] POTS telephone signals have a frequency of about 3 kHz, close to the baseband audio frequency.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] Cable television and other cable-transmitted information currents may alternate at frequencies of tens to thousands of megahertz.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] These frequencies are similar to the electromagnetic wave frequencies often used to transmit the same types of information over the air.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] The first alternator to produce alternating current was an electric generator based on Michael Faraday's principles constructed by the French instrument maker Hippolyte Pixii in 1832.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] Pixii later added a commutator to his device to produce the (then) more commonly used direct current.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] The earliest recorded practical application of alternating current is by Guillaume Duchenne, inventor and developer of electrotherapy.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] In 1855, he announced that AC was superior to direct current for electrotherapeutic triggering of muscle contractions.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] Alternating current technology was developed further by the Hungarian Ganz Works company in the 1870s, and, in the 1880s, by Sebastian Ziani de Ferranti, Lucien Gaulard, and Galileo Ferraris.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] In 1876, Russian engineer Pavel Yablochkov invented a lighting system where sets of induction coils were installed along a high-voltage AC line.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] Instead of changing voltage, the primary windings transferred power to the secondary windings which were connected to one or several electric candles (arc lamps) of his own design, used to keep the failure of one lamp from disabling the entire circuit.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] In 1878, the Ganz factory, Budapest, Hungary, began manufacturing equipment for electric lighting and, by 1883, had installed over fifty systems in Austria-Hungary.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] Their AC systems used arc and incandescent lamps, generators, and other equipment.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] The development of the alternating current transformer to change voltage from low to high level and back, allowed generation and consumption at low voltages and transmission, over great distances, at high voltage, with savings in the cost of conductors and energy losses.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] A bipolar open-core power transformer developed by Lucien Gaulard and John Dixon Gibbs was demonstrated in London in 1881, and attracted the interest of Westinghouse.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] They exhibited an AC system powering arc and incandescent lights was installed along five railway stations for the Metropolitan Railway in London and a single-phase multiple-user AC distribution system Turin in 1884.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] These early induction coils with open magnetic circuits were inefficient at transferring power to loads.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] Until about 1880, the paradigm for AC power transmission from a high voltage supply to a low voltage load was a series circuit.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] Open-core transformers with a ratio near 1:1 were connected with their primaries in series to allow use of a high voltage for transmission while presenting a low voltage to the lamps.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] The inherent flaw in this method was that turning off a single lamp (or other electronic device) affected the voltage supplied to all others on the same circuit.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] Many adjustable transformer designs were introduced to compensate for this problematic characteristic of the series circuit, including those employing methods of adjusting the core or bypassing the magnetic flux around part of a coil.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] The direct current systems did not have these drawbacks, giving it significant advantages over early AC systems.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] In 1890, he designed their power station at Deptford and converted the Grosvenor Gallery station across the Thames into an electrical substation, showing the way to integrate older plants into a universal AC supply system.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] In the autumn of 1884, Károly Zipernowsky, Ottó Bláthy and Miksa Déri (ZBD), three engineers associated with the Ganz Works of Budapest, determined that open-core devices were impractical, as they were incapable of reliably regulating voltage.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] In both designs, the magnetic flux linking the primary and secondary windings traveled almost entirely within the confines of the iron core, with no intentional path through air (see toroidal cores).
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] The new transformers were 3.4 times more efficient than the open-core bipolar devices of Gaulard and Gibbs.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] The Ganz factory in 1884 shipped the world's first five high-efficiency AC transformers.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] This first unit had been manufactured to the following specifications: 1,400 W, 40 Hz, 120:72 V, 11.6:19.4 A, ratio 1.67:1, one-phase, shell form.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] When employed in parallel connected electric distribution systems, closed-core transformers finally made it technically and economically feasible to provide electric power for lighting in homes, businesses and public spaces.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] The other essential milestone was the introduction of 'voltage source, voltage intensive' (VSVI) systems' by the invention of constant voltage generators in 1885.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] In early 1885, the three engineers also eliminated the problem of eddy current losses with the invention of the lamination of electromagnetic cores.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] Ottó Bláthy also invented the first AC electricity meter.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] In May 1885, at the Hungarian National Exhibition in Budapest, Deri, Blathy, and Zipernowski held a large-scale demonstration of what is widely regarded as the prototype of modern AC lighting systems.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] Their system used 75 transformers in parallel connection, supplying 1,067 incandescent Edison lamps from an AC generator that provided 1,350 V.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] The AC power system was developed and adopted rapidly after 1886.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] With this setup, the Westinghouse company successfully powered thirty 100-volt incandescent bulbs in twenty shops along the main street of Great Barrington.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] By the fall of that year Ganz engineers installed a ZBD transformer power system with AC generators in Rome.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] Based on Stanley's success, the new Westinghouse Electric went on to develop alternating current (AC) electric infrastructure throughout the United States.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] The spread of Westinghouse and other AC systems triggered a push back in late 1887 by Thomas Edison (a proponent of direct current), who attempted to discredit alternating current as too dangerous in a public campaign called the "war of the currents".
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] In 1888, alternating current systems gained further viability with the introduction of a functional AC motor, something these systems had lacked up till then.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] The design, an induction motor, was independently invented by Galileo Ferraris and Nikola Tesla (with Tesla's design being licensed by Westinghouse in the US).
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] This design was independently further developed into the modern practical three-phase form by Mikhail Dolivo-Dobrovolsky and Charles Eugene Lancelot Brown in Germany on one side, and Jonas Wenström in Sweden on the other, though Brown favored the two-phase system.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] The Ames Hydroelectric Generating Plant, constructed in 1890, was among the first hydroelectric alternating current power plants.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] A long-distance transmission of single-phase electricity from a hydroelectric generating plant in Oregon at Willamette Falls sent power fourteen miles downriver to downtown Portland for street lighting in 1890.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] In 1891, another transmission system was installed in Telluride Colorado.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] The first three-phase system was established in 1891 in Frankfurt, Germany.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] The Tivoli–Rome transmission was completed in 1892.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] The San Antonio Canyon Generator was the third commercial single-phase hydroelectric AC power plant in the United States to provide long-distance electricity.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] It was completed on December 31, 1892, by Almarian William Decker to provide power to the city of Pomona, California, which was 14 miles away.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] Meanwhile, the possibility of transferring electrical power from a waterfall at a distance was explored at the Grängesberg mine in Sweden.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] A 45 m fall at Hällsjön, Smedjebackens kommun, where a small iron work had been located, was selected.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] In 1893, a three-phase 9.5 kv system was used to transfer 400 horsepower a distance of 15 km, becoming the first commercial application.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] In 1893, Westinghouse built an alternating current system for the Chicago World Exposition.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] In 1893, Decker designed the first American commercial three-phase power plant using alternating current—the hydroelectric Mill Creek No.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] 1 Hydroelectric Plant near Redlands, California.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] Decker's design incorporated 10 kV three-phase transmission and established the standards for the complete system of generation, transmission and motors used in USA today.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] The original Niagara Falls Adams Power Plant with three two-phase generators was put into operation in August 1895, but was connected to the remote transmission system only in 1896.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] The Jaruga Hydroelectric Power Plant in Croatia was set in operation two days later, on 28 August 1895.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] Its generator (42 Hz, 240 kW) was made and installed by the Hungarian company Ganz, while the transmission line from the power plant to the City of Šibenik was 11.5 kilometers (7.1 mi) long, and the municipal distribution grid 3000 V/110 V included six transforming stations.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] Alternating current circuit theory developed rapidly in the latter part of the 19th and early 20th century.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] Notable contributors to the theoretical basis of alternating current calculations include Charles Steinmetz, Oliver Heaviside, and many others.
[src:bristol-409/alternating-current] Calculations in unbalanced three-phase systems were simplified by the symmetrical components methods discussed by Charles LeGeyt Fortescue in 1918.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] An **alternator** (or **synchronous generator**) is an electrical generator that converts mechanical energy to electrical energy in the form of alternating current (AC).
[src:bristol-409/alternator] For reasons of cost and simplicity, most alternators use a rotating magnetic field with a stationary armature.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] The rotor coil is externally excited by a small direct current (DC), while the AC is generated in the stationary coils.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] Occasionally, a linear alternator or a rotating armature with a stationary magnetic field is used.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] Although any AC electrical generator might be called an alternator, usually the term refers to small rotating machines driven by automotive and other internal combustion engines.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] The term usually applies those types with externally excited rotor coils.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] An alternator that uses a permanent magnet for its magnetic field is called a magneto.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] Alternators in power stations driven by steam turbines are called turbo-alternators.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] Large 50 or 60 Hz three-phase alternators in power plants generate most of the world's electric power, which is distributed by electric power grids.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] Alternating current generating systems were known in simple forms from the discovery of the magnetic induction of electric current in the 1830s.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] Rotating generators naturally produced alternating current, but since there was little use for it, it was normally converted into direct current via the addition of a commutator in the generator.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] The early machines were developed by pioneers such as Michael Faraday and Hippolyte Pixii.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] Faraday developed the "rotating rectangle", whose operation was *heteropolar* – each active conductor passed successively through regions where the magnetic field was in opposite directions.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] Lord Kelvin and Sebastian Ferranti also developed early alternators, producing frequencies between 100 and 300 Hz.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] The late 1870s saw the introduction of the first large-scale electrical systems with central generation stations to power Arc lamps, used to light whole streets, factory yards, or the interior of large warehouses.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] Some, such as Yablochkov arc lamps introduced in 1878, ran better on alternating current, and the development of these early AC generating systems was accompanied by the first use of the word "alternator".
[src:bristol-409/alternator] Supplying the proper amount of voltage from generating stations in these early systems was left up to the engineer's skill in "riding the load".
[src:bristol-409/alternator] In 1883 the Ganz Works invented the constant voltage generator that could produce a stated output voltage, regardless of the value of the actual load.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] The introduction of transformers in the mid-1880s led to the widespread use of alternating current and the use of alternators needed to produce it.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] After 1891, polyphase alternators were introduced to supply currents of multiple differing phases.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] Later alternators were designed for various alternating current frequencies between sixteen and about one hundred hertz for use with arc lighting, incandescent lighting, and electric motors.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] Specialized radio frequency alternators like the Alexanderson alternator were developed as longwave radio transmitters around World War 1 and used in a few high power wireless telegraphy stations before vacuum tube transmitters replaced them.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] A conductor moving relative to a magnetic field develops an electromotive force (EMF) in it (Faraday's Law).
[src:bristol-409/alternator] This EMF reverses its polarity when it moves under magnetic poles of opposite polarity.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] Typically, a rotating magnet, called the rotor, turns within a stationary set of conductors, called the stator, wound in coils on an iron core.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] The field cuts across the conductors, generating an induced EMF (electromotive force), as the mechanical input causes the rotor to turn.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] The rotating magnetic field induces an AC voltage in the stator windings.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] Since the currents in the stator windings vary in step with the position of the rotor, an alternator is a synchronous generator.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] The rotor's magnetic field may be produced by permanent magnets or by a field coil electromagnet.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] Automotive alternators use a rotor winding, which allows control of the alternator's generated voltage by varying the current in the rotor field winding.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] Permanent magnet machines avoid the loss due to magnetizing current in the rotor, but are restricted in size due to the cost of the magnet material.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] Since the permanent magnet field is constant, the terminal voltage varies directly with the speed of the generator.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] Brushless AC generators are usually larger than those used in automotive applications.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] An automatic voltage control device controls the field current to keep the output voltage constant.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] If the output voltage from the stationary armature coils drops due to an increase in demand, more current is fed into the rotating field coils through the voltage regulator (VR).
[src:bristol-409/alternator] This increases the magnetic field around the field coils, which induces a greater voltage in the armature coils.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] Thus, the output voltage is brought back up to its original value.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] Alternators used in central power stations also control the field current to regulate reactive power and to help stabilize the power system against the effects of momentary faults.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] Often, there are three sets of stator windings, physically offset so that the rotating magnetic field produces a three-phase current, displaced by one-third of a period with respect to each other.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] One cycle of alternating current is produced each time a pair of field poles passes over a point on the stationary winding.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] The relation between speed and frequency is $N=120f/P$ , where f is the frequency in Hz (cycles per second).
[src:bristol-409/alternator] P is the number of poles (2, 4, 6, ...), and N is the rotational speed in revolutions per minute (r/min).
[src:bristol-409/alternator] Old descriptions of alternating current systems sometimes give the frequency in terms of alternations per minute, counting each half-cycle as one *alternation*; so 12,000 alternations per minute corresponds to 100 Hz.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] An alternator's output frequency depends on the number of poles and the rotational speed.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] The speed corresponding to a particular frequency is called the *synchronous speed*.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] Alternators may be classified by the method of excitation, number of phases, the type of rotation, cooling method, and their application.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] There are two main ways to produce the magnetic field used in the alternators: by using permanent magnets, which create their persistent magnetic field, or by using field coils.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] The alternators that use permanent magnets are specifically called magnetos.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] In other alternators, wound field coils form an electromagnet to produce the rotating magnetic field.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] A device that uses permanent magnets to produce alternating current is called a permanent magnet alternator (PMA).
[src:bristol-409/alternator] A permanent magnet generator (PMG) may produce either alternating current or direct current if it has a commutator.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] This method of excitation consists of a smaller direct-current (DC) generator fixed on the same shaft as the alternator.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] The DC generator generates a small amount of electricity, just enough to *excite* the field coils of the connected alternator to generate electricity.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] A variation of this system is a type of alternator that uses direct current from a battery for initial excitation upon start-up, after which the alternator becomes self-excited.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] This method of excitation consists of a smaller alternating-current (AC) generator fixed on the same shaft as the alternator.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] The AC stator generates a small amount of field coil excitation current, which is induced in the rotor and rectified to DC by a bridge rectifier built in to the windings where it excites the field coils of the larger connected alternator to generate electricity.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] This system has the advantage of not requiring brushes, which increases service life, although with a slightly lower overall efficiency.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] This method depends on residual magnetism retained in the iron core to generate a weak magnetic field, which would allow a weak voltage to be generated.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] This voltage is used to excite the field coils so the alternator can generate stronger voltage as part of its *build up* process.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] After the initial AC voltage buildup, the field is supplied with rectified voltage from the alternator.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] A brushless alternator is composed of two alternators built end-to-end on one shaft.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] Until 1966, alternators used brushes with rotating field.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] With the advancement in semiconductor technology, brushless alternators are possible.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] Smaller brushless alternators may look like one unit, but the two parts are readily identifiable in the large versions.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] The main alternator is the larger of the two sections, and the smaller one is the exciter.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] The exciter has stationary field coils and a rotating armature (power coils).
[src:bristol-409/alternator] The main alternator uses the opposite configuration with a rotating field and stationary armature.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] A bridge rectifier, called the rotating rectifier assembly, is mounted on the rotor.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] Neither brushes nor slip rings are used, which reduces the number of wearing parts.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] The main alternator has a rotating field and a stationary armature (power generation windings).
[src:bristol-409/alternator] Varying the amount of current through the stationary exciter field coils varies the 3-phase output from the exciter.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] This output is rectified by a rotating rectifier assembly mounted on the rotor, and the resultant DC supplies the rotating field of the main alternator and hence alternator output.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] The result is that a small DC exciter current indirectly controls the output of the main alternator.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] Another way to classify alternators is by the number of phases of their output voltage.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] The output can be single-phase or polyphase.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] Three-phase alternators are the most common, but polyphase alternators can be two-phase, six-phase, or more.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] The revolving part of alternators can be the armature or the magnetic field.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] The revolving armature type has the armature wound on the rotor, where the winding moves through a stationary magnetic field.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] The revolving armature type is not often used.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] The revolving field type has a magnetic field on the rotor to rotate through a stationary armature winding.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] The stationary armature can be wound for any convenient medium voltage level, up to tens of thousands of volts; manufacture of slip ring connections for more than a few thousand volts is costly and inconvenient.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] Many alternators are cooled by ambient air, forced through the enclosure by an attached fan on the shaft that drives the alternator.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] In vehicles such as transit buses, a heavy demand on the electrical system may require a large alternator to be oil-cooled.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] In marine applications water-cooling is also used.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] Expensive automobiles may use water-cooled alternators to meet high electrical system demands.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] Most power generation stations use synchronous machines as their generators.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] The connection of these generators to the utility grid requires synchronization conditions to be met.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] Synchronous generators provide several important system services.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] Their inherent rotational inertia slows the initial frequency decline after a sudden loss of generation, allowing turbine governors and other frequency-control reserves time to respond and restore balance.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] This role is increasingly significant as the share of non-synchronous generation, such as solar photovoltaics and many modern wind plants, grows in many power systems.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] Alternators are used in modern internal combustion engine automobiles to charge the battery and to power the electrical system when its engine is running.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] Until the 1960s, automobiles used DC dynamo generators with commutators.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] With the availability of affordable silicon-diode rectifiers, alternators were used instead.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] In later diesel–electric locomotives and diesel–electric multiple units, the prime mover turns an alternator which provides electricity for the traction motors (AC or DC).
[src:bristol-409/alternator] The traction alternator usually incorporates integral silicon diode rectifiers to provide the traction motors with up to 1,200 volts DC.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] The first diesel electric locomotives, and many of those still in service, use DC generators as, before silicon power electronics, it was easier to control the speed of DC traction motors.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] Most of these had two generators: one to generate the excitation current for a larger main generator.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] Optionally, the generator also supplies head-end power (HEP) or power for electric train heating.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] The HEP option requires a constant engine speed, typically 900 r/min for a 480 V 60 Hz HEP application, even when the locomotive is not moving.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] Marine alternators used in yachts are similar to automotive alternators, with appropriate adaptations to the salt-water environment.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] Marine alternators are designed to be explosion proof (ignition protected) so that brush sparking will not ignite explosive gas mixtures in an engine room environment.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] Depending on the type of system installed, they may be 12 or 24 volts.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] Larger marine diesels may have two or more alternators to cope with the heavy electrical demand of a modern yacht.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] On single alternator circuits, the power may be split between the engine starting battery and the domestic or house battery (or batteries) by use of a split-charge diode (battery isolator) or a voltage-sensitive relay.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] Due to the high cost of large house battery banks, Marine alternators generally use external regulators.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] Multistep regulators control the field current to maximize the charging effectiveness (time to charge) and battery life.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] Multistep regulators can be programmed for different battery types.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] Two temperature sensors can be added: one for the battery to adjust the charging voltage and an over-temperature sensor on the actual alternator to protect it from overheating.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] High-frequency alternators of the variable-reluctance type were applied commercially to radio transmission in low-frequency radio bands.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] These were used for transmitting Morse code and, experimentally, for transmitting voice and music.
[src:bristol-409/alternator] In the Alexanderson alternator, both the field winding and armature winding are stationary, and current is induced in the armature by the changing magnetic reluctance of the rotor (which has no windings or current-carrying parts).
[src:bristol-409/alternator] Such machines were made to produce radio frequency current for radio transmissions, although the efficiency was low.
[src:bristol-409/autocar-magazine] The publication was launched as *The Autocar* by Iliffe and Son Ltd.
[src:bristol-409/autocar-magazine] "in the interests of the mechanically propelled road carriage" on 2 November 1895 when, it is believed, there were only six or seven cars in the United Kingdom.
[src:bristol-409/autocar-magazine] Setright suggests that the magazine was set up by Henry Sturmey as an organ of propaganda for Harry J.
[src:bristol-409/autocar-magazine] Lawson, founder of the Daimler Company and a journalist on the magazine in its early days.
[src:bristol-409/autocar-magazine] Henry Sturmey stood down as editor of *The Autocar* magazine and left the company in 1901.
[src:bristol-409/autocar-magazine] The magazine's name was changed from *The Autocar* to *Autocar* at the start of 1962.
[src:bristol-409/autocar-magazine] In 1988 *Autocar* absorbed the rival magazine *Motor*, with which it had done battle on the newsstands since 1903.
[src:bristol-409/autocar-magazine] From the 7 September 1988 issue the magazine became *Autocar & Motor*.
[src:bristol-409/autocar-magazine] It reverted to *Autocar* for the 21 September 1994 issue.
[src:bristol-409/autocar-magazine] The magazine has scored many firsts in its history, including the first full road tests and independent performance tests of the Jaguar XJ220, McLaren F1, and the Porsche 911 GT1.
[src:bristol-409/autocar-magazine] It was also the first magazine to produce independently recorded performance figures for the Bugatti Veyron, which were published in the 31 May 2006 issue.
[src:bristol-409/autocar-magazine] In 2023, *Autocar* digitised its entire archive dating back to 1895.
[src:bristol-409/autocar-magazine] The Autocar Archive is available to subscribers online.
[src:bristol-409/autocar-magazine] In the 1950s, the magazine's sport editor, John Cooper, used Cooper T11 parts to create the Cooper-Alta.
[src:bristol-409/autocar-magazine] Former *Autocar* writers include Russell Bulgin, Chris Harris, and former *Top Gear* presenter James May.
[src:bristol-409/autocar-magazine] In 1992, May was fired from *Autocar* after he added an acrostic into the 1992 "Road Test Yearbook".
[src:bristol-409/autocar-magazine] May had to write every review in the issue.
[src:bristol-409/autocar-magazine] Each spread featured four reviews and each review started with a big red capital letter known as a rubricated initial.
[src:bristol-409/autocar-magazine] May was bored and to alleviate the boredom, he wrote the reviews so the first four spreads would spell the words "ROAD", "TEST", "YEAR" and "BOOK".
[src:bristol-409/autocar-magazine] The other pages had another acrostic but that was not immediately recognizable as it was spread over the rest of the magazine, spelling seemingly random letters starting with "SOYO" and "UTHI".
[src:bristol-409/autocar-magazine] After it was published, readers discovered it.
[src:bristol-409/autocar-magazine] This was the one that got James May fired because it used profanity.
[src:bristol-409/autocar-magazine] The message, when punctuated was: "So you think it's really good, yeah?
[src:bristol-409/autocar-magazine] Current *Autocar* writers include Richard Bremner, used car expert James Ruppert, Editor at Large Matt Prior and Editor in Chief Steve Cropley.
[src:bristol-409/autocar-magazine] The current editor is Mark Tisshaw, a former deputy editor, news editor and reporter for the magazine.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] An **automatic transmission** (**AT**) or **automatic gearbox** is a multi-speed transmission used in motor vehicles that does not require any input from the driver other than throttle position to change forward gears under normal driving conditions.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] The 1904 Sturtevant "horseless carriage gearbox" is often considered to be the first true automatic transmission.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] The first mass-produced automatic transmission was General Motors' Hydra-Matic, introduced in Oldsmobile models for the 1940 model year.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] Automatic transmissions are especially prevalent in vehicular drivetrains, particularly those subject to intense mechanical acceleration and frequent idle/transient operating conditions; commonly commercial/passenger/utility vehicles, such as buses and waste collection vehicles.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] Vehicles with internal combustion engines, unlike electric vehicles, require the engine to operate in a narrow range of rates of rotation, requiring a gearbox, operated manually or automatically, to drive the wheels over a wide range of speeds.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] Globally, 43% of new cars produced in 2015 were manual transmissions, falling to 37% by 2020.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] Automatic transmissions have long been prevalent in the United States, but only started to become common in Europe much later.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] In Europe in 1997, only 10–12% of cars had automatic transmissions.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] In 1957 over 80% of new cars in the United States had automatic transmissions.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] Automatic transmissions have been standard in large cars since at least 1974.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] By 2020 only 2.4% of new cars had manual transmissions.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] Historically, automatic transmissions were less efficient, but lower fuel prices in the US made this less of a problem than in Europe.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] In the United Kingdom, a majority of new cars have had automatic transmissions since 2020.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] Several manufacturers including Mercedes and Volvo no longer sell cars with manual transmissions.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] The growing prevalence of automatic transmissions is attributed to the increasing number of electric and hybrid cars, and the ease of integrating it with safety systems such as Autonomous Emergency Braking.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] The efficiency (power output as a percentage of input) of conventional automatic transmissions ranges from 86 to 94%.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] Manual transmissions are more fuel efficient than all but the newest automatic transmissions due to their inherently low parasitic losses (typically of about 4%) in addition to being cheaper to make, lighter, better performing, and of simpler mechanical design.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] Fuel economy worsens with lower efficiency.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] However, manual transmissions require the driver to operate the clutch and change gear whenever required.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] Real-world tests reported in 2022 found that in typical driving manual transmissions achieved 2 to 5% better fuel economy than automatics, increasing to 20% with an expert driver.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] Some laboratory tests show automatics in a better light due to the tests using a prescribed shifting pattern for manuals not always optimized for economy.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] However, on long highway journeys manual transmissions require maintaining a very specific cruising speed to optimise economy, making automatics preferable.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] The most common design of automatic transmissions is the hydraulic automatic, which typically uses planetary gearsets that are operated using hydraulics.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] The transmission is connected to the engine via a torque converter (or a fluid coupling prior to the 1960s), instead of the friction clutch used by most manual transmissions.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] A hydraulic automatic transmission uses planetary gearsets instead of the manual transmission's design of gears lined up along input, output and intermediate shafts.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] To change gears, the hydraulic automatic uses a combination of internal clutches, friction bands or brake packs.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] These devices are used to lock certain gears, thus setting which gear ratio is in use at a given time.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] A sprag clutch (a ratchet-like device which can freewheel and transmits torque in only one direction) is often used for routine gear shifts.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] The advantage of a sprag clutch is that it eliminates the sensitivity of timing a simultaneous clutch release/apply on two planetary gearsets, simply "taking up" the drivetrain load when actuated, and releasing automatically when the next gear's sprag clutch assumes the torque transfer.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] The friction bands are often used for manually selected gears (such as low range or reverse) and operate on the planetary drum's circumference.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] Bands are not applied when the drive/overdrive range is selected, the torque being transmitted by the sprag clutches instead.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] The aforementioned friction bands and clutches are controlled using automatic transmission fluid (ATF), which is pressurized by a pump and then directed to the appropriate bands/clutches to obtain the required gear ratio.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] The ATF provides lubrication, corrosion prevention, and a hydraulic medium to transmit the power required to operate the transmission.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] Made from petroleum with various refinements and additives, ATF is one of the few parts of the automatic transmission that needs routine service as the vehicle ages.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] The *main pump* which pressurises the ATF is typically a gear pump mounted between the torque converter and the planetary gear set.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] The input for the main pump is connected to the torque converter housing, which in turn is bolted to the engine's flexplate, so the pump provides pressure whenever the engine is running.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] The pressure of the ATF is regulated by a *governor* connected to the output shaft, which varies the pressure depending on the vehicle speed.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] The *valve body* inside the transmission is responsible for directing hydraulic pressure to the appropriate bands and clutches.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] It receives pressurized fluid from the main pump and consists of several spring-loaded valves, check balls, and servo pistons.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] In older automatic transmissions, the valves use the pump pressure and the pressure from a centrifugal governor on the output side (as well as other inputs, such as throttle position or the driver locking out the higher gears) to control which ratio is selected.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] As the vehicle and engine change speed, the difference between the pressures changes, causing different sets of valves to open and close.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] In more recent automatic transmissions, the valves are controlled by solenoids.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] These solenoids are computer-controlled, with the gear selection decided by a dedicated transmission control unit (TCU) or sometimes this function is integrated into the engine control unit (ECU).
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] Modern designs have replaced the centrifugal governor with an electronic speed sensor that is used as an input to the TCU or ECU.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] Modern transmissions also factor in the amount of load on an engine at any given time, which is determined from either the throttle position or the amount of intake manifold vacuum.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] The multitude of parts, along with the complex design of the valve body, originally made hydraulic automatic transmissions much more expensive and time-consuming to build and repair than manual transmissions; however mass-production and developments over time have reduced this cost gap.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] To provide coupling and decoupling of the engine, a modern automatic transmission uses a torque converter instead of the friction clutch used in a manual transmission.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] The 1904 Sturtevant "horseless carriage gearbox" is often considered to be the first automatic transmission for motor vehicles.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] At higher engine speeds, high gear was engaged.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] As the vehicle slowed down and engine speed decreased, the gearbox would shift back to low.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] However, the transmission was prone to sudden failure, due to the transmission being unable to withstand forces from the abrupt gear changes.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] The adoption of planetary gearsets was a significant advance towards the modern automatic transmission.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] One of the first transmissions to use this design was the manual transmission fitted to the 1901–1904 Wilson-Pilcher automobile.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] This transmission was built in the United Kingdom and used two epicyclic gears to provide four gear ratios.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] A foot clutch was used for standing starts, gear selection was using a hand lever, helical gears were used (to reduce noise) and the gears used a constant-mesh design.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] A planetary gearset was also used in the 1908 Ford Model T, which was fitted with a two-speed manual transmission (without helical gears).
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] An early patent for the automatic transmission was granted to Canadian inventor Alfred Horner Munro of Regina in 1923.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] Being a steam engineer, Munro designed his device to use compressed air rather than hydraulic fluid, and so it lacked power and never found commercial application.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] In 1923, a patent was approved in the United States describing the operation of a transmission where the manual shifting of gears and manual operation of a clutch was eliminated.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] Hoffman from Chicago and was titled: *Automatic Gear Shift and Speed Control*.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] However, it would be over a decade later until automatic transmissions were produced in significant quantities.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] In the meantime, several European and British manufacturers would use preselector gearboxes, a form of manual transmission which removed the reliance on the driver's skill to achieve smooth gear shifts.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] The first automatic transmission using hydraulic fluid was developed in 1932 by two Brazilian engineers, José Braz Araripe and Fernando Lehly Lemos.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] The evolution towards mass-produced automatic transmissions continued with the 1933–1935 REO Motor Car Company *Self-Shifter* semi-automatic transmission, which automatically shifted between two forward gears in the "Forward" mode (or between two shorter gear ratios in the "Emergency low" mode).
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] Driver involvement was still required during normal driving, since standing starts required the driver to use the clutch pedal.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] This was followed in 1937 by the Oldsmobile *Automatic Safety Transmission*.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] Similar in operation to the REO *Self-Shifter*, the *Automatic Safety Transmission* shifted automatically between the two gear ratios available in the "Low" and "High" ranges and the clutch pedal was required for standing starts.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] The Chrysler *Fluid Drive*, introduced in 1939, was an optional addition to manual transmissions where a fluid coupling (similar to a torque-convertor, but without the torque multiplication) was added, to avoid the need to operate a manual clutch.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] The General Motors Hydra-Matic became the first mass-produced automatic transmission following its introduction in 1939 (1940 model year).
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] Available as an option in cars such as the Oldsmobile Series 60 and Cadillac Sixty Special, the Hydra-Matic combined a fluid coupling with three hydraulically controlled planetary gearsets to produce four forward speeds plus reverse.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] The transmission was sensitive to engine throttle position and road speed, producing fully automatic up- and down-shifting that varied according to operating conditions.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] During World War II, the Hydra-Matic was used in some military vehicles.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] The first automatic transmission to use a torque converter (instead of a fluid coupling) was the Buick Dynaflow, which was introduced for the 1948 model year.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] In normal driving, the Dynaflow used only the top gear, relying on the torque multiplication of the torque convertor at lower speeds.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] The Dynaflow was followed by the Packard Ultramatic in mid-1949 and the Chevrolet Powerglide for the 1950 model year.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] Each of these transmissions had only two forward speeds, relying on the converter for additional torque multiplication.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] In the early 1950s, BorgWarner developed a series of three-speed torque converter automatics for car manufacturers such as American Motors, Ford and Studebaker.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] Chrysler was late in developing its own true automatic, introducing the two-speed torque converter PowerFlite in 1953, and the three-speed TorqueFlite in 1956.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] The latter was the first to utilize the Simpson compound planetary gearset.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] In 1956, the General Motors Hydra-Matic (which still used a fluid coupling) was redesigned based around the use of two fluid couplings to provide smoother shifts.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] This transmission was called the *Controlled Coupling Hydra-Matic*, or "Jetaway" transmission.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] The original Hydra-Matic remained in production until the mid-1960s at GM, with the licensed Rolls-Royce Automatic transmission soldiering on until 1978 on the Rolls-Royce Phantom VI.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] In 1964, General Motors released a new transmission, the Turbo Hydramatic, a three-speed transmission which used a torque convertor.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] The Turbo Hydramatic was among the first to have the basic gear selections (*park*, *reverse*, *neutral*, *drive*, *low*) which became the standard gear selection used for several decades.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] By the late 1960s, most of the fluid-coupling two-speed and four-speed transmissions had disappeared in favor of three-speed units with torque converters.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] Also around this time, whale oil was removed from the automatic transmission fluid.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] During the 1980s, automatic transmissions with four gear ratios became increasingly common, and many were equipped with lock-up torque convertors in order to improve fuel economy.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] Electronics began to be more commonly used to control the transmission, replacing mechanical control methods such as spring-loaded valves in the valve body.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] Most systems use solenoids which are controlled by either the engine control unit, or a separate transmission control unit.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] This allows for more precise control of shift points, shift quality, lower shift times and manual control.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] The first five-speed automatic was the Jatco 5R01, introduced in 1989 by Nissan in the Cedric and Gloria, and was electronically controlled.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] The first six-speed automatic was the ZF 6HP26 transmission, which debuted in the 2002 BMW 7 Series (E65).
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] The first seven-speed automatic was the Mercedes-Benz 7G-Tronic transmission, which debuted a year later.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] In 2007, the first eight-speed transmission to reach production was the Toyota AA80E transmission.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] The first nine-speed and ten-speed transmissions were the 2013 ZF 9HP transmission and 2017 *Toyota Direct Shift-10A* (used in the Lexus LC) respectively.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] The gear selector is the input by which the driver selects the operating mode of an automatic transmission.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] A few automobiles employed a lever on the instrument panel, such as the 1955 Chrysler Corporation cars, and notably, the Corvair.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] Some automatic transmissions, especially by General Motors from 1940 to 1964, used a layout with *reverse* as the bottom position (e.g.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] Many transmissions also include positions to restrict the gear selection to the lower gears and engages the engine brake.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] These positions are often labelled "L" (low gear), "S" (second gear) or the number of the highest gear used in that position (eg 3, 2 or 1).
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] If these positions are engaged at a time when it would result in excessive engine speed, many modern transmissions disregard the selector position and remain in the higher gear.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] Many modern transmissions include modes to adjust the shift logic to prefer either power or fuel economy.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] "Sport" (also called "Power" or "Performance") modes cause gear shifts to occur at higher engine speeds, allowing higher acceleration.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] "Economy" (also called "Eco" or "Comfort") modes cause gear shifts to occur at lower engine speeds to reduce fuel consumption.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] Since the 1990s, systems to manually request a specific gear or an upshift/downshift have become more common.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] These *manumatic* transmissions offer the driver greater control over the gear selection that the traditional modes to restrict the transmission to the lower gears.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] Use of the manumatic functions are typically achieved either via paddles located beside the steering column, or "+" and "-" controls on the gear selector.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] Some cars offer drivers both methods to request a manual gear selection.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] A *continuously variable transmission* (CVT) can change seamlessly through a continuous (infinite) range of gear ratios, compared with other automatic transmissions that provide a limited number of gear ratios in fixed steps.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] The flexibility of a CVT with suitable control may allow the engine to operate at a constant angular velocity while the vehicle moves at varying speeds.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] CVTs are used in cars, tractors, UTVs, motor scooters, snowmobiles, and earthmoving equipment.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] The most common type of CVT uses two pulleys connected by a belt or chain.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] However, several other designs have also been used.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] A *dual-clutch transmission* (DCT, sometimes referred to as a *twin-clutch transmission*, or *double-clutch transmission*) uses two separate clutches for odd and even gear sets.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] The design is often similar to two separate manual transmissions with their respective clutches contained within one housing, and working as one unit.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] In most car and truck applications, the DCT functions as an automatic transmission, requiring no driver input to change gears.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] The first DCT to reach production was the *Easidrive* automatic transmission introduced on the 1961 *Hillman Minx* mid-size car.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] This was followed by various eastern European tractors through the 1970s (using manual operation via a single clutch pedal), then the *Porsche 962 C* racing car in 1985.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] The first DCT of the modern era was used in the 2003 *Volkswagen Golf R32*.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] Since the late 2000s, DCTs have become increasingly widespread, and have supplanted hydraulic automatic transmissions in various models of cars.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] Modern versions of these systems that are fully automatic in operation, such as *Selespeed* and *Easytronic*, require no driver input over gear changes or clutch operation.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] Semi-automatic versions require only partial driver input (i.e., the driver must change gears manually), while fully automatic versions require no manual driver input, whatsoever (TCU or ECU operates both the clutch system and gear shifts automatically).
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] Modern automated manual transmissions (AMT) have their roots and origins in older clutchless manual transmissions that began to appear on mass-production automobiles in the early 1930s and 1940s, prior to the introduction of hydraulic automatic transmissions.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] These systems were designed to reduce the amount of clutch or gear shifter usage required by the driver.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] These devices were intended to reduce the difficulty of operating conventional unsynchronised manual transmissions ("crash gearboxes") that were commonly used at the time, especially in stop-start driving.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] An early example of this transmission was introduced with the Hudson Commodore in 1942, called *Drive-Master*.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] Another early example of this transmission system was introduced in the 1955 Citroën DS, which used a 4-speed *BVH* transmission.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] This semi-automatic transmission used an automated clutch, which was actuated using hydraulics.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] Gear selection also used hydraulics, however, the gear ratio needs to be manually selected by the driver.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] This system was nicknamed *Citro-Matic* in the U.S.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] The first modern AMTs were introduced by BMW and Ferrari in 1997, with their *SMG* and *F1* transmissions, respectively.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] Both systems used hydraulic actuators and electrical solenoids, and a designated transmission control unit (TCU) for the clutch and shifting, plus steering wheel-mounted paddle shifters, if the driver wanted to change gear manually.
[src:bristol-409/automatic-transmission] Modern fully automatic AMTs, such as *Selespeed* and *Easytronic*, have now been largely superseded and replaced by the increasingly widespread dual-clutch transmission design.
[src:bristol-409/bristol-400] The **Bristol 400** is a luxury car made by the Bristol Cars division of the Bristol Aeroplane Company.
[src:bristol-409/bristol-400] Manufactured from 1947 to 1950, it was the first model of car that the company made.
[src:bristol-409/bristol-400] As World War II progressed, Bristol Aircraft considered its future, which resulted in forming a car division in 1945, later becoming the Bristol Cars company in its own right.
[src:bristol-409/bristol-400] Engineers from Bristol inspected the Soviet-controlled BMW factory at Eisenach in the Soviet occupation zone in Germany, and returned to Britain with plans for the BMW 327 and the BMW six-cylinder engine as official war reparations.
[src:bristol-409/bristol-400] Bristol then employed BMW engineer Fritz Fiedler to lead its engine development team.
[src:bristol-409/bristol-400] In 1946 Bristol Aircraft acquired a majority shareholding in Frazer Nash, which in the 1930s held a licence to build the BMW 328.
[src:bristol-409/bristol-400] In 1947 the newly-formed Bristol Cars released its 400 coupé.
[src:bristol-409/bristol-400] It is a lengthened version of the BMW 327, and features BMW's double-kidney radiator grille.
[src:bristol-409/bristol-400] Bristol based the 400 on the best features of two outstanding pre-war BMWs: the engine of the 328, and the chassis of the 326.
[src:bristol-409/bristol-400] These were covered with a mainly steel body but with aluminium bonnet, door and boot skins inspired by the 327.
[src:bristol-409/bristol-400] The 400 has a slightly modified version of BMW's six-cylinder pushrod engine of 1,971 cc (bore 66 mm, stroke 96 mm).
[src:bristol-409/bristol-400] This engine, considered advanced for its time due to its hemispherical combustion chambers and very short inlet and exhaust ports, develops 80 horsepower at 4,500 rpm, and gives the car a top speed of about 148 km/h (92 mph), with acceleration to match.
[src:bristol-409/bristol-400] In order to form a hemispherical combustion chamber, the valves are positioned at an angle to the head.
[src:bristol-409/bristol-400] In order to drive both sets of valves from a single camshaft, the Bristol engine uses a system of rods, followers and bell-cranks to drive the valves on the far side of the engine from the camshaft.
[src:bristol-409/bristol-400] Owners soon found that setting and maintaining the numerous clearances in the system was difficult, but vital to keep the engine in tune.
[src:bristol-409/bristol-400] The gearbox is a four-speed manual with synchromesh on the upper three ratios and a freewheel in first.
[src:bristol-409/bristol-400] The 400 is the only Bristol that has a steel and aluminium skin.
[src:bristol-409/bristol-400] It has all flat glass, apart from the curved rear window, which is glazed in Perspex, and was available to specification with a top hinge.
[src:bristol-409/bristol-400] This was very welcome on warmer climate export markets, where the sliding door windows provided only marginal ventilation to the occupants.
[src:bristol-409/bristol-400] The 400 has independent front suspension with a transverse leaf spring and a live axle, located by an A-bracket over the differential case, and longitudinal torsion bars with transverse arms and brackets at the rear.
[src:bristol-409/bristol-400] It has a lengthy 2,895 mm (114.0 in) wheelbase and a very BMW-like grille at the front of its long bonnet.
[src:bristol-409/bristol-400] The passenger area is very short, with the spare tyre mounted inside the boot on the first cars.
[src:bristol-409/bristol-400] In later 400s the spare wheel is mounted on the rear hinged boot lid, inside an aluminium cover.
[src:bristol-409/bristol-400] Battista Pininfarina designed an alternative body for the 400.
[src:bristol-409/bristol-400] Its lines prefigure the 400's successor model, the 401, which Bristol launched in 1948.
[src:bristol-409/bristol-401] The **Bristol 401** saloon and **Bristol 402** cabriolet are British luxury grand tourers, produced between 1948 and 1953 by Bristol Cars, an offshoot of the Bristol Aeroplane Company They were developed from the Bristol 400, which continued in production alongside the 401 and 402 until 1950.
[src:bristol-409/bristol-401] The 401 and 402 use an improved version of the BMW 328 hemispherical-head engine and its unusual arrangement of two separate pushrods to operate the exhaust valves, necessitated by the hemispherical combustion chambers and opposite facing valves, as used in the 400.
[src:bristol-409/bristol-401] However, the styling was an advance on that first Bristol model.
[src:bristol-409/bristol-401] It was inspired by a Milanese designer, Carrozzeria Touring, and its most notable feature is that the door handles are not exposed.
[src:bristol-409/bristol-401] The doors are opened by pressing a button in the door.
[src:bristol-409/bristol-401] The body is more spacious than the 400, and is a full five-seater.
[src:bristol-409/bristol-401] At the front the 401 and 402 are also distinctive, with their headlights positioned quite a distance toward the centre-line of the body, either side of the narrow grille, which resembles BMW grille a little less than does the 400's.
[src:bristol-409/bristol-401] They are also deeply curved at the front: this, along with the then-unique door handle arrangement, is believed to give the 401 a drag coefficient of less than Cd 0.36 – competitive even by today's standards and remarkable for the time.
[src:bristol-409/bristol-401] The engine is the same 2-litre in-line six-cylinder petrol unit as in the 400, but upgraded with improved Solex carburettors to increase power by 5 bhp (3.7 kW) to 85 bhp (63 kW).
[src:bristol-409/bristol-401] This improved the performance further beyond what was achieved by the aerodynamics.
[src:bristol-409/bristol-401] The suspension is independent at the front, using a transverse leaf spring and wishbones.
[src:bristol-409/bristol-401] The rigid axle at the rear has torsion bars.
[src:bristol-409/bristol-401] The brakes are Lockheed hydraulic, with 11 in (279 mm) drums all round.
[src:bristol-409/bristol-401] Bristol made 611 401s, which is still the largest production run of any Bristol model.
[src:bristol-409/bristol-401] However, it made only 23 402s, which makes it one of the rarest historic cars of its era.
[src:bristol-409/bristol-401] In a recent survey, 13 of those 23 were accounted for.
[src:bristol-409/bristol-401] A saloon tested by *The Motor* magazine in 1952 recorded a top speed of 97.3 mph (156.6 km/h), and accelerated from 0 to 60 mph (97 km/h) in 15.1 seconds.
[src:bristol-409/bristol-401] A fuel consumption of 20.8 miles per imperial gallon (13.6 L/100 km; 17.3 mpg‑US) was recorded.
[src:bristol-409/bristol-401] The test car cost £3,532 including taxes.
[src:bristol-409/bristol-401] Referring to that road test in a 1971 "classic car" feature, the journal summarised the 401 as a "Medium-sized car offering very high standards of comfort and performance".
[src:bristol-409/bristol-401] Four examples of a 401 Cabriolet with styling by Pininfarina were also built.
[src:bristol-409/bristol-403] The **Bristol 403** is a luxury car which was produced from 1953 to 1955 by British manufacturer Bristol Aeroplane Co.
[src:bristol-409/bristol-403] (whose car division later became Bristol Cars).
[src:bristol-409/bristol-403] The 403 was the third of the eventual five series of Bristols powered by the BMW-derived pushrod straight-six engine.
[src:bristol-409/bristol-403] It replaced the Bristol 401 and 402 in 1953 and continued in production for two years.
[src:bristol-409/bristol-403] It retained much the same styling as the 401, but featured many mechanical improvements compared to that model.
[src:bristol-409/bristol-403] The 1971 cc six-cylinder engine was modified through the use of bigger valves and larger main bearings with a diameter of 54 mm as against 51 mm on the 400 and 401, which increased the power output to 100 hp (75 kW) as against 85 hp (63 kW) on the 401.
[src:bristol-409/bristol-403] The acceleration was markedly improved: the 403 could reach 60 miles per hour (97 km/h) in 13.4 seconds as against 16.4 seconds for the 401.
[src:bristol-409/bristol-403] The 403 had top speed of 104 miles per hour (167 km/h).
[src:bristol-409/bristol-403] To cope with this increased power, an anti-roll bar was fitted on the front suspension and improved drum brakes known as "Alfins" (Aluminum finned) were fitted.
[src:bristol-409/bristol-403] Early models had them on all wheels, but Bristol thought the car was over-braked and they were thus restricted to the front wheels on later 403s.
[src:bristol-409/bristol-403] The 403 was the last Bristol to feature a BMW-style radiator grille.
[src:bristol-409/bristol-403] It is also noteworthy for having two extra headlamps at the side, almost pre-dating the adoption of the four-headlamp layout in larger cars (Bristol themselves adopted it with the 411 in the late 1960s).
[src:bristol-409/bristol-409] The **Bristol 409** was the third series of cars from British manufacturer Bristol Cars powered by Chrysler V8 engines.
[src:bristol-409/bristol-409] It was actually introduced before the older Bristol 408 went out of production and only gradually supplanted that model after a year.
[src:bristol-409/bristol-409] There were a number of major changes to the chassis of the 409 compared to earlier Bristols.
[src:bristol-409/bristol-409] The springs were much softer than of the 408 or 407, so that the ride quality was much better.
[src:bristol-409/bristol-409] Following on from Chrysler's pioneering work in the early 1960s, Bristol fitted an alternating current alternator in place of the traditional direct current dynamo, which had proven difficult to drive at high engine speeds.
[src:bristol-409/bristol-409] Also a follow-up to previous work on the 408 was an improved safety lever to prevent anyone from putting the automatic transmission in gear accidentally.
[src:bristol-409/bristol-409] There was also an altered differential fitted with a slightly higher (*i.e.* numerically lower) ratio.
[src:bristol-409/bristol-409] The styling was almost unchanged from the 408, though the radiator grille was now altered into a trapezoidal shape rather than the precise rectangle of the 408.
[src:bristol-409/bristol-409] The engine was also altered slightly – remaining at 5,211 cc (318.0 cubic inches) but providing slightly increased power and torque.
[src:bristol-409/bristol-409] The 409 was the first Bristol to be offered with power steering, initially as an optional extra but after June 1967 as a standard feature.
[src:bristol-409/bristol-409] The 409 was the last Bristol V8 to feature dashboard transmission selector buttons.
[src:bristol-409/bristol-409] The subsequent Bristol 410 sported a central transmission shift lever, as well as a more streamlined frontal design.
